4 8–327.
5 (a) (1) There is a board of property review in each county.
6 (2) If necessary, additional boards may be appointed in any county.
7 (b) (1) Each board of property review of a county has three members who are
8 appointed by the judges of the circuit court for the county.
9 (2) Of the members of each board:
10 (i) One shall be a lawyer;
11 (ii) One shall be a farmer engaged in some agricultural pursuit; and
12 (iii) One shall be an engineer or a person with an engineering
13 background and knowledge.
14 (3) A member of the General Assembly may not be a member of a board
15 during his term of office.
16 (c) (1) Each board member serves for a term of 2 years and until his successor
17 is appointed and qualifies.
18 (2) A member appointed to fill a vacancy in an unexpired term serves only
19 for the remainder of that term.
20 (d) A board member is entitled to the per diem compensation set by the Supreme
21 Court of Maryland. The compensation shall be uniform statewide and shall be paid monthly
22 by the Commission, on vouchers approved by the clerk of the court.
23 (e) Each board shall appoint its chairman and may adopt rules not inconsistent
24 with this title or the Maryland Rules.
25 (f) Each county shall provide a suitable place for its board to meet and, whenever
26 possible, the clerk of the court shall provide suitable clerical assistance. If the clerk fails to
27 provide clerical assistance, the Administration OR THE MARYLAND TRANSIT
28 ADMINISTRATION, AS APPROPRIATE, shall provide it on request of the board.
29 (g) Each board is under the jurisdiction of the court and each member of the board
30 is an officer of the court.
31 8–328.

SENATE BILL 947 23
1 (a) Each board of property review:
2 (1) Shall hear promptly all cases certified to it by the Commission OR THE
3 MARYLAND TRANSIT ADMINISTRATION;
4 (2) Shall determine the total amount of the award to be paid by the
5 Commission OR THE MARYLAND TRANSIT ADMINISTRATION; and
6 (3) May determine the portion of an award to be paid to persons, other than
7 the fee owner, who have an interest in the property.
8 (b) Unless all parties in a case certified to a board agree otherwise, the full board
9 shall hear and decide the case. If a member of the board is absent or disqualified from
10 hearing or deciding any case, the judges of the court that appointed the board shall
11 designate another individual with qualifications similar to those of the absent or
12 disqualified member to serve instead.
13 (c) The board shall determine the fair value of the property to be acquired as of
14 the date payment is made under § 7–401.1 OR § 7–401.2 OF THIS ARTICLE OR § 8–323
15 of this subtitle.
16 8–329.
17 If any party is dissatisfied with the findings or award of a board of property review,
18 the case may be appealed to the court. On appeal, the court shall hear and determine the
19 case de novo, as provided by law and the Maryland Rules.
20 SECTION 4. 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, notwithstanding § 7–201.1
21 of the Transportation Article, as enacted by Section 1 of this Act, the initial terms of the
22 Board of Directors for Baltimore Core Transit Service established under this Act shall be
23 staggered as follows:
24 (1) the five members appointed by the Governor shall serve an initial term
25 of 4 years; and
26 (2) the members appointed by the Mayor of Baltimore City, the Baltimore
27 County Executive, and the Anne Arundel County Executive shall serve an initial term of 3
28 years.
29 SECTION 5. 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, notwithstanding § 7–201.2
30 of the Transportation Article, as enacted by Section 1 of this Act, the initial terms of the
31 Commuter Services Advisory Board established under this Act shall be staggered as
32 follows:

24 SENATE BILL 947
1 (1) of the six members who reside in areas served by MARC or Maryland
2 Transit Administration commuter buses, three members shall serve an initial term of 4
3 years and three members shall serve an initial term of 3 years;
4 (2) the member who represents riders with accessibility challenges shall
5 serve an initial term of 4 years; and
6 (3) the member who is an employee of a Maryland Transit Administration
7 commuter service contractor and is a member of a labor union that has a collective
8 bargaining agreement with the commuter service contractor shall serve an initial term of
9 3 years.
10 SECTION 6. 4. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
11 (a) The Department of Transportation shall contract with the Baltimore
12 Metropolitan Council to complete a technical study on or before December 1, 2026, that:
13 (1) provides findings and considerations on the creation of a rail authority
14 in Maryland, with the intent that this rail authority would be focused on financing for rail
15 services;
16 (2) examines peer models that may provide insight for the findings and
17 considerations, including models in the Commonwealth of Virginia and Austin, Texas;
18 (3) provides potential next steps to consider in the creation of a rail
19 authority in Maryland; and
20 (4) ensures that current rail transit services remain under the Maryland
21 Transit Administration and that funding options for a statewide rail authority do not
22 undermine future financial support for Baltimore Core Transit Services.
23 (b) The Baltimore Metropolitan Council may consult with the Metropolitan
24 Washington Council of Governments in completing the technical study.
25 SECTION 7. 5. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the Maryland Transit
26 Administration shall:
27 (1) reallocate its staff to ensure sufficient support for the Board of Directors
28 for Baltimore Core Transit Service and the Commuter Services Advisory Board; and
29 (2) at a minimum establish the following staff positions:
30 (i) a Deputy Administrator and an analyst for the Board of Directors
31 for Baltimore Core Transit Service;
32 (ii) a Deputy Administrator and an analyst for the Commuter
33 Services Advisory Board; and

SENATE BILL 947 25
1 (iii) a support officer to be shared between the Board of Directors for
2 Baltimore Core Transit Service and the Commuter Services Advisory Board.
3 SECTION 8. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the General Assembly
4 determines that the amendment to the Maryland Constitution proposed by Section 2 of this
5 Act affects multiple jurisdictions and that the provisions of Article XIV, § 1 of the Maryland
6 Constitution concerning local approval of constitutional amendments do not apply.
7 SECTION 9. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the amendment to the
8 Maryland Constitution proposed by Section 2 of this Act shall be submitted to the qualified
9 voters of the State at the next general election to be held in November 2026 for adoption or
10 rejection in accordance with Article XIV of the Maryland Constitution. At that general
11 election, the vote on the proposed amendment to the Constitution shall be by ballot, and on
12 each ballot there shall be printed the words “For the Constitutional Amendment” and
13 “Against the Constitutional Amendment”, as now provided by law. Immediately after the
14 election, all returns shall be made to the Governor of the vote for and against the proposed
15 amendment, as directed by Article XIV of the Maryland Constitution, and further
16 proceedings held in accordance with Article XIV.
17 SECTION 10. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That Section 3 of this Act is
18 contingent on the passage of Section 2 of this Act, a constitutional amendment, and its
19 ratification by the voters of the State.
20 SECTION 11. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, subject to Section 10 of this
21 Act, Section 3 of this Act shall take effect on the proclamation of the Governor that the
22 constitutional amendment, having received a majority of the votes cast at the general
23 election, has been adopted by the people of Maryland.
24 SECTION 12. 6. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, except as provided in
25 Sections 9 and 11 of this Act, this Act shall take effect October 1, 2026.
Approved:
